If I could give a lower rating than one star, I would. Visited this place at 12:30pm on Tuesday, June 5th...despite the lunch hour, and it being conveniently located next door to the convention center where a very large convention was happening this week, there were very few people in the restaurant. I was there with a colleague and our business guest, who is an older adult and has difficulty hearing. We requested a table in a quiet section so that we could readily conduct a business discussion at a volume comfortable for our guest. Despite the fact that there were quiet sections available, the table we were given was not accommodating enough, and as the hostess had hurried off already, we picked up our menus and moved ourselves to a table in a quieter section. It happened to be in the bar area, where no other tables were occupied. As it turns out there were little signs noting that to receive service, anyone seated at these select tables needed to take their menu order requests to the person tending the bar. When I couldn’t flag down anyone who would even make eye contact with us for the first 15 minutes we were seated, I approached a waitress to request that service be provided to our table (as it was the only table occupied in the bar and necessary to select the table to accommodate our business guest’s ability to hear). I was interrupted abruptly and told that all orders had to be given to the bartender...no exceptions. I was then rudely reminded that their policy is directly spelled out on the sign on each table, so there would be no accommodation allowed. So at the suggestion of our older guest, we moved back to a table where service would be provided so that we could at least have a chance at eating food over our lunch meeting. Within a couple of minutes of seating ourselves back in the original section, a less-than-happy waitress arrived to throw drink napkins in front of each of us and mumble something to the effect that she would be back to take our orders. After waiting another 10 minutes (which by this time was nearly halfway through our anticipated one-hour meeting), no one had arrived to take our orders and didn’t seem in any hurry to do so...again, despite the fact that most of the restaurant was empty. Ultimately, we decided to leave the restaurant in favor of another restaurant located within the hotel (Anthem), where we received prompt and attentive service, and were ultimately able to conduct a productive meeting. I understand that the name of the place includes the phrase “sports bar”...I do not however believe that should be an excuse for the rude, extremely limited, and poor service that we received. Good luck to this place if the business model allows for customer experiences similar to ours.

Here's the thing. I was more hungry than anything, and to be honest the food was whatever. I got a burger and a chicken noodle soup. Burger was average and the soup was decent. That's not why I gave this 5 stars though. I sat at the bar with the two people I was dining with and I had the honor of having Steve as my bartender.  HE WAS AWESOME.  Incredibly knowledgeable about drinks and recommendations which any good bartender should but he had a personality that was more than I ever could have asked for. If I were to open a bar that's the guy I would want running the show. If you EVER have the chance to pop in there for a drink, have him whip you up something and just chat with him. Super awesome, great to get to know, incredibly funny and situationally intelligent. I had him whip me up a custom version of their Moscow Mule and I ordered another just to sit there and chat longer.  Do what I did, go for a random reason and stay for the Steve. If you don't sit at the bar while he's working you're really dropping the ball.  Cheers!

What is the policy regarding return emails?  Called six day in a row.  No one answers there.  No managerial presence and the event planner "Victoria? Veronica? (I finally was patched through on the seventh day by the staff of the actual hotel) is unapologetic, unaccomodating and not at all customer service oriented.   Blech.

I did have something irritating happen to me twice recently.  I live here and often walk to HV.  They close at 1am on Fridays, but twice I've gotten to their front door before 12:10am and it was locked.  You have to go alllll the way around the block and enter through the hotel. It's quite a walk when it's 90º outside and you've been working all day. When I got in the restaurant the 2nd time, I asked why the front doors were locked.  They said last call was at 12:30am, so they lock the doors so people don't walk in after last call..... which didn't make sense since I was asking this question at 12:16am and the doors were locked around 12am.  When I questioned this answer, the bartender basically made a joke about how I could use the exercise and the conversation was dropped.  Get the door locking situation fixed and it's a 5-star review.  Otherwise, minus 2 stars for inconvenience and a lack of reasonable explanation.
